    <section class="chapter" id="venice">
        <header class="chapter__header">
            <div class="chapter__counter">part two</div>
            <h2 class="chapter__title">
                <span>Venice</span>
            </h2>
            <p class="chapter__meta">January 9–13 · 4 nights</p>
        </header>

        <figure class="chapter__image drift">
            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523906834658-6e24ef2386f9?w=900&q=80" 
                 alt="Venice Grand Canal" 
                 width="900" height="600" loading="lazy">
            <figcaption>La Serenissima in winter light</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="prose">
            <p>Venice in January is Venice without the crowds—a city returned to itself. The light is different in winter: softer, more forgiving, turning every canal into a mirror and every building into a watercolor. We're staying in Dorsoduro, the quietest of the central sestieri, where the Accademia and Guggenheim are neighbors and the views across to the Giudecca make evening walks feel like stepping into a Canaletto.</p>
            
            <p>Il Palazzo Experimental is the kind of hotel that feels like a discovery—design-forward but warm, stylish but not trying too hard. The kind of place where breakfast becomes an event and the bar becomes a ritual.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">Il Palazzo Experimental</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Dorsoduro 1411, Venice</div>
            <div class="lodging__conf">Conf#415560872</div>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>The Days</h3>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Friday, January 9</span>
            </div>
            <p>We land at Marco Polo just before noon. The water taxi will be extravagant and worth it—approaching Venice by water is the only proper introduction. Afternoon to settle in, perhaps a first visit to the <strong>Accademia</strong> if energy permits, then an easy dinner in the neighborhood.</p>
            <p><em>Flight: Air France AF1426, CDG 10:00 → VCE 11:45</em></p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Saturday, January 10</span>
            </div>
            <p>Art immersion day. Morning at the <strong>Gallerie dell'Accademia</strong>—Bellini, Titian, Tintoretto, Veronese, the whole Venetian pantheon. Afternoon at the <strong>Peggy Guggenheim Collection</strong>, then <strong>Punta della Dogana</strong> for the contemporary counterpoint. Evening aperitivo somewhere with a view.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Sunday, January 11</span>
            </div>
            <p>The classics: <strong>St. Mark's Basilica</strong> (check Sunday hours), the <strong>Doge's Palace</strong>, then wandering through the Arsenale and Biennale district. Late afternoon through San Polo to Rialto, then the Line 1 vaporetto at sunset—the Grand Canal gilded and glowing.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Monday, January 12</span>
            </div>
            <p>Islands day. <strong>Murano</strong> in the morning to watch glass being shaped by fire. <strong>Burano</strong> in the afternoon for lunch among the colored houses. Back to Venice for a farewell dinner—Osteria da Fiore if we can get in, Antiche Carampane if we can't, Alle Testiere if we're lucky.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

