        <div class="prose">
            <p>Milan is not a city that reveals itself easily. It lacks the obvious beauty of Rome or Florence, the romance of Venice, the glamour of the Riviera. What it has instead is something rarer: a kind of sophisticated intensity, a city where design and industry and fashion and art have fused into something uniquely Milanese.</p>
            
            <p>We're staying in Ticinese, the neighborhood that feels most like the Milan of the Milanese—the Navigli canals, the vintage shops, the aperitivo bars that haven't been discovered by Instagram yet.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">Airbnb</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Corso di Porta Ticinese 12, Milan 20123</div>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>The Days</h3>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Sunday, January 18</span>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Pinacoteca di Brera</strong> in the morning—one of Italy's great collections, in a building that feels like a Renaissance palace because it was one. Then the <strong>Duomo</strong>: the roof terraces first (book tickets), then the interior. Evening in Brera for aperitivo and dinner.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Monday, January 19</span>
            </div>
            <p>Contemporary Milan. <strong>Fondazione Prada</strong> in the morning—Rem Koolhaas's architectural masterpiece, housing Miuccia Prada's impeccable collection. Lunch at <strong>Bar Luce</strong>, Wes Anderson's candy-colored café. Afternoon wandering through Porta Nuova and the <strong>Bosco Verticale</strong>. Dinner in Isola.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Tuesday, January 20</span>
            </div>
            <p><strong>The Last Supper.</strong> Fifteen minutes in front of Leonardo's masterpiece—booked months ago, because this is how it works. Then Corso Magenta and the design district, <strong>10 Corso Como</strong> for the shop that started it all.</p>
            <p><em>Book months ahead: cenacolovinciano.org</em></p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Wednesday, January 21</span>
            </div>
            <p>Flexible day. <strong>Castello Sforzesco</strong> if we want more art, <strong>Museo del Novecento</strong> if we want more modernism, Navigli canals if we want to just walk. Shopping in the Quadrilatero if we want to dream. Pack for Como.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Thursday, January 22</span>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Lake Como day.</strong> Train to Varenna first (one hour, beautiful), then ferry to Bellagio for lunch, then Como town. The Brunate funicular at sunset if timing works. One night at Hotel Villa Flori—a villa on the lake.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">Hotel Villa Flori</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Lake Como, one night</div>
            <div class="lodging__conf">Conf#CY295UL56868</div>
        </div>
    </section>

