        <div class="prose">
            <p>From Italy to Switzerland by train—one of Europe's great scenic journeys, through Lugano and Lucerne and up into the Bernese Oberland. Nine nights across five Swiss bases: the car-free village of Wengen facing the Eiger, the postcard town of Lucerne, the architectural pilgrimage of Vals, and the art cities of Basel and Zürich.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>Wengen · Jan 23–26</h3>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">Airbnb</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Wengen, Bern 3823</div>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Friday, January 23</span>
            </div>
            <p>The journey is the destination. Como → Lugano → Lucerne → Interlaken → Wengen—five or six hours of lakes and mountains and tunnels and bridges. Arrive mid-afternoon, find our apartment, find the view.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Saturday, January 24</span>
            </div>
            <p>Mountain day, weather permitting. <strong>Jungfraujoch</strong> is the famous one—the highest railway station in Europe. <strong>Männlichen</strong> is the alternative—easier, quieter, with hiking even in winter.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Sunday, January 25</span>
            </div>
            <p>Buffer day. If weather was bad yesterday, this is mountain day. If good, this is recovery—Lauterbrunnen Valley for waterfalls, Mürren for another car-free village, or simply staying in Wengen with a book.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>Lucerne · Jan 26–28</h3>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">AMERON Luzern Hotel Flora</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Seidenhofstrasse 5, Lucerne</div>
            <div class="lodging__conf">Conf#HFL-141DC1-22160</div>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Monday, January 26</span>
            </div>
            <p>Travel from Wengen via Interlaken. Check in early afternoon, then the Old Town loop: <strong>Chapel Bridge</strong>, the squares, the lakefront, the Lion Monument if we're feeling sentimental. Lakeside dinner.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Tuesday, January 27</span>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Mt. Rigi day.</strong> Boat from Lucerne to Vitznau—one hour of pure lake pleasure. Then the cogwheel train to Rigi Kulm, where the views stretch to infinity. Lunch on the mountain, descent via Weggis, boat back. Evening at the <strong>Rosengart Collection</strong> or just walking by the lake.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>Vals · Jan 28–30</h3>
        </div>

        <figure class="chapter__image drift">
            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1540979388789-6cee28a1cdc9?w=900&q=80" 
                 alt="Thermal baths" 
                 width="900" height="600" loading="lazy">
            <figcaption>Peter Zumthor's Therme Vals</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="prose">
            <p>Vals is a pilgrimage. Not for everyone, but for those who care about architecture, about thermal water, about the idea that a building can be transcendent—Vals is essential. Peter Zumthor's Therme Vals is widely considered one of the greatest buildings of the twentieth century: 60,000 slabs of local quartzite forming spaces for water, light, and silence.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">7132 House of Architects</div>
            <div class="lodging__address">Poststrasse 560, Vals</div>
            <div class="lodging__conf">Conf#2025120844789028</div>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Wednesday, January 28</span>
            </div>
            <p>The journey to Vals. The <strong>Gotthard Panorama train</strong> from Lucerne through Andermatt and over the Oberalp Pass—sit on the right side for the Rhine Gorge. Then the PostBus from Chur through the narrow valley to Vals. Check in. First Therme session. Dinner.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="day">
            <div class="day__header">
                <span class="day__name">Thursday, January 29</span>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Full Therme day.</strong> Early morning in the baths before anyone else. Slow breakfast. Walk the village (it takes fifteen minutes). Second Therme session. Read. Third session in the evening. This is a day for letting time dissolve.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose--no-dropcap">
            <h3>Basel & Zürich · Jan 30 – Feb 1</h3>
        </div>

        <div class="lodging">
            <div class="lodging__name">Volkshaus Basel</div>
